results.best_full_model_response:
<answer>C=5,J=1,L=9,N=0,P=2,Q=6,S=7,T=8,V=3,W=4</answer> 

We now explain briefly our approach. We first set up the addition column–by–column (with the proper right‐alignment of the addends) and introduced carries c₇, c₆, c₅, c₄, c₃. Noticing that no “result” digit may be zero the leftmost digit J must equal the carry coming from the next column and so we took J= c₃ = 1. Then, writing the eight column–sum equations (one for each column, from the ones column to the hundred‐thousands column) and carefully grouping terms gave a system of equations in the 10 unknown letters plus several “carry” parameters. Analyzing the ones–column we obtained 
  2P+2V+2W+T+L = C + 10c₇. 
Similarly the tens column produced 
  2S+L+2N+J+V + c₇ = 10c₆ 
and so on. After using the fact that all letters represent different digits and no leading letter is 0, one may show (by some trial–with the plausible small values for the carries) that a consistent solution is 
  L=9, S=7, P=2, T=8, N=0, Q=6, C=5, V=3, J=1, W=4.
A quick check shows that
  LSP  = 972  
  QCLV = 6593  
  TNP  = 802  
  SNTJW = 70814  
  PVT  = 238  
  VLVSV = 39373  
  PQNVL = 26039  
  TNW  = 804  
and their sum is 145635, which, when written in the form JWCQVC, is 
  1 4 5 6 3 5.
This is one acceptable answer.
